(97, 178, 1, 3, '2025-06-18', 'June Week 1 - World Environment Day – June 5th. Repeat the CW', 'World Environment Day – June 5th.\r\n\r\n\r\nWorld Environment Day is celebrated every year on June 5th to raise awareness and take action for the protection of our environment. It was started by the United Nations in 1972, and each year focuses on a different theme related to nature and the planet’s health.\r\n\r\nWhy It Matters:\r\n\r\nIt reminds us to reduce pollution, save trees, conserve water, and protect wildlife.\r\n\r\nEvery small step—like planting a tree, reducing plastic use, or saving electricity—can help.\r\n\r\nThe Earth is our only home. Keeping it clean and green is our responsibility.', NULL),
(98, 181, 1, 3, '2025-06-18', 'June Week 1 - World Environment Day – June 5th. Repeat the CW', 'World Environment Day – June 5th.\r\n\r\n\r\nWorld Environment Day is celebrated every year on June 5th to raise awareness and take action for the protection of our environment. It was started by the United Nations in 1972, and each year focuses on a different theme related to nature and the planet’s health.\r\n\r\nWhy It Matters:\r\n\r\nIt reminds us to reduce pollution, save trees, conserve water, and protect wildlife.\r\n\r\nEvery small step—like planting a tree, reducing plastic use, or saving electricity—can help.\r\n\r\nThe Earth is our only home. Keeping it clean and green is our responsibility.', NULL),
(100, 182, 1, 1, '2025-06-18', 'June Week 1 - Unicorn  - Print and color', 'Mythical Creature\r\nA legendary animal that looks like a horse but has:\r\n\r\nA single spiraling horn on its forehead.\r\n\r\nOften associated with purity, grace, and magic.\r\n\r\nCommon in folklore, fantasy stories, and children’s media', 'uploads/homework_attachments/72a2aaa7084a9cbd_WhatsApp Image 2025-06-18 at 09.50.21_e375a073.jpg'),
(110, 185, 1, 5, '2025-06-18', 'ladybugs', 'Fun Facts About Ladybugs\r\nNot Really a Bug!\r\n\r\nDespite their name, ladybugs are actually a type of beetle, not a true bug.\r\n\r\nBright Colors = Stay Away!\r\n\r\nTheir bright red or orange bodies with black spots are a warning to predators: “I taste bad!”\r\n\r\nGreat Garden Helpers\r\n\r\nLadybugs love to eat aphids (tiny pests), so they help protect plants and gardens.\r\n\r\nMany, Many Types\r\n\r\nThere are over 5,000 species of ladybugs around the world!\r\n\r\nSpots Aren’t for Age\r\n\r\nSome people think a ladybug’s spots tell its age, but that’s a myth! Spots help identify the species.\r\n\r\nThey Can “Play Dead”\r\n\r\nWhen scared, ladybugs might stop moving and even release a smelly liquid to fool predators.\r\n\r\nWinter Sleep\r\n\r\nIn cold weather, ladybugs go into a kind of sleep called hibernation and often gather in big groups.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/015fbe7338eecc9f_ladybug color pencil week 4.png'),
(111, 187, 1, 5, '2025-06-18', 'ladybugs', 'Fun Facts About Ladybugs\r\nNot Really a Bug!\r\n\r\nDespite their name, ladybugs are actually a type of beetle, not a true bug.\r\n\r\nBright Colors = Stay Away!\r\n\r\nTheir bright red or orange bodies with black spots are a warning to predators: “I taste bad!”\r\n\r\nGreat Garden Helpers\r\n\r\nLadybugs love to eat aphids (tiny pests), so they help protect plants and gardens.\r\n\r\nMany, Many Types\r\n\r\nThere are over 5,000 species of ladybugs around the world!\r\n\r\nSpots Aren’t for Age\r\n\r\nSome people think a ladybug’s spots tell its age, but that’s a myth! Spots help identify the species.\r\n\r\nThey Can “Play Dead”\r\n\r\nWhen scared, ladybugs might stop moving and even release a smelly liquid to fool predators.\r\n\r\nWinter Sleep\r\n\r\nIn cold weather, ladybugs go into a kind of sleep called hibernation and often gather in big groups.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/015fbe7338eecc9f_ladybug color pencil week 4.png'),
(112, 189, 9, 4, '2025-06-18', 'HW- Great Crested Grebe', 'Crested head feathers: The adult has distinctive black crests and chestnut \"ear tufts.\"\r\n\r\nSharp, pointed beak: Adapted for catching fish.\r\n\r\nElegant neck: Long and white with a graceful curve.\r\n\r\nYoung chicks: Often ride on the parent\'s back and have striped heads.\r\n\r\nThey’re known for their graceful swimming, elaborate mating dances, and are often found on freshwater lakes and rivers.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/ccbc8c327f3f74c1_Enhanced june w1.png'),
(114, 187, 1, 5, '2025-06-19', 'Fred Flintstone  Cartoon Character', 'Fred Flintstone is the main character of the animated sitcom The Flintstones, which aired during prime-time on ABC during the original series\' run from 1960 to 1966.\r\nFred is the husband of Wilma Flintstone and father of Pebbles Flintstone and together the family live in their homely cave in the town of Bedrock. His best friend is his next door neighbor, Barney, who has a wife named Betty.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/4b82009092c526bb_cartoon C.png'),
(116, 187, 1, 5, '2025-06-26', 'HW- Boat', 'A boat sails gently across the sea,\r\nDancing with waves so wild and free.\r\nIts wooden hull strong, yet light as air.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/60d0e81183b2d41a_week 2 june.png'),
(117, 178, 1, 3, '2025-06-20', 'HW - Draw Rainbow Lorikeet', 'The Rainbow Lorikeet was abundant around Sydney until the late 19th century, but was rare in Sydney between then and 1950. It is now highly abundant again across Sydney.\r\n\r\nThe Rainbow Lorikeet is unmistakable with its bright red beak and colourful plumage. Both sexes look alike, with a blue (mauve) head and belly, green wings, tail and back, and an orange/yellow breast. They are often seen in loud and fast-moving flocks, or in communal roosts at dusk.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/27aee4b5205f6a63_rainbow.jpg'),
(118, 181, 1, 3, '2025-06-20', 'HW - Draw Rainbow Lorikeet', 'The Rainbow Lorikeet was abundant around Sydney until the late 19th century, but was rare in Sydney between then and 1950. It is now highly abundant again across Sydney.\r\n\r\nThe Rainbow Lorikeet is unmistakable with its bright red beak and colourful plumage. Both sexes look alike, with a blue (mauve) head and belly, green wings, tail and back, and an orange/yellow breast. They are often seen in loud and fast-moving flocks, or in communal roosts at dusk.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/27aee4b5205f6a63_rainbow.jpg'),
(119, 183, 1, 2, '2025-06-20', 'HW - print & color Rainbow Lorikeet', 'The Rainbow Lorikeet was abundant around Sydney until the late 19th century, but was rare in Sydney between then and 1950. It is now highly abundant again across Sydney.\r\n\r\nThe Rainbow Lorikeet is unmistakable with its bright red beak and colourful plumage. Both sexes look alike, with a blue (mauve) head and belly, green wings, tail and back, and an orange/yellow breast. They are often seen in loud and fast-moving flocks, or in communal roosts at dusk.', 'uploads/homework_attachments/6a642cef7e8c3ff3_12133.jpg'),
(124, 195, 3, 5, '2025-06-21', 'HW -ladybugs', 'About **ladybugs**\r\n\r\n🐞 **1. Tiny Superheroes!**\r\nLadybugs eat plant-eating bugs like aphids — they help protect gardens and farms just like superheroes!\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n🌈 **2. Dots Are Their Style!**\r\nMost ladybugs have **red or orange bodies** with **black spots** — no two ladybugs have the same dot pattern!\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n🛡️ **3. Bright Colors = Warning!**\r\nTheir bright color tells predators: \"Don’t eat me — I taste bad!\" 😝\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n🪺 **4. From Egg to Bug**\r\nLadybugs grow from **eggs to larvae to adults** — just like butterflies, they go through a cool life cycle!\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n🎉 **5. Lucky Bugs!**\r\nIn many cultures, **seeing a ladybug is a sign of good luck**. Some people even make wishes when they see one!', 'uploads/homework_attachments/04f2e8740915fc82_ladybug color pencil week 4.png'),
